# Minimal API Patterns

## Endpoint Group Pattern

```csharp
public static class UserEndpoints
{
    public static RouteGroupBuilder MapUserEndpoints(this WebApplication app)
    {
        var group = app.MapGroup("/api/users")
            .WithTags("Users")
            .RequireAuthorization();

        group.MapGet("/", GetAllUsers);
        group.MapGet("/{id}", GetUserById);
        group.MapPost("/", CreateUser);
        group.MapPut("/{id}", UpdateUser);
        group.MapDelete("/{id}", DeleteUser);

        return group;
    }

    private static async Task<Results<Ok<UserResponse>, NotFound>> GetUserById(
        int id, IUserService userService, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var user = await userService.GetByIdAsync(id, ct);
        return user is not null
            ? TypedResults.Ok(user)
            : TypedResults.NotFound();
    }
}
```

## Conventions

- Use `TypedResults` for all responses — enables OpenAPI schema generation
- Group endpoints with `MapGroup()` and apply shared filters/auth
- Add `FluentValidation` for input models — validate in an endpoint filter
- Accept `CancellationToken` in all async handlers
- Return `Results<T1, T2>` union types for multiple response codes
- Register endpoint groups in `Program.cs`: `app.MapUserEndpoints()`
- Keep handlers thin — delegate to service layer via DI
